@NODE "BitPosition" "BitPosition"
@TOC "MAIN"

Function         : BitPosition

Prototype        : short BitPosition( LONG bitpattern);

Purpose          : find the actual position of the highest SET bit in bitpattern
                   consider the expression (z = 1L << y)..  this function, when
                   given z will return the value of y.

Arguments        : bitpattern - the bit mask to examine

Returns          : the actual position of the highest SET bit in bitpattern

Known bugs       : none

See also         :
@ENDNODE

@NODE "BuildDir" "BuildDir"
@TOC "MAIN"

Function         : BuildDir

Prototype        : short BuildDir( char *path );

Purpose          : Create the disk structure specified by a given path

Arguments        : path - a string containing the path to be created if
                   non-existant

Returns          : TRUE if path created or already existant
                   FALSE if path could not be created

Known bugs       : none
@ENDNODE

@NODE "CNetAddressToAccount" "CNetAddressToAccount"
@TOC "MAIN"

Function         : CNetAddressToAccount

Prototype        : short CNetAddressToAccount( char *a );

Purpose          : find the account number that corresponds to a given CNet mail
                   ID (AKA username or @{"UUCP" LINK "cnetinclude:users.h/main" 154} ID)

Arguments        : a - the mail ID to examine

Returns          : the account number associated with the given mail ID

                   note some special case mappings:
                   
                      AREAFIX and ROOT map to account #1
                      FEEDBACK maps to fake account -1
                      NEWUSER maps to fake account -2
                      SYSOP maps to fake account -3

                   a return value of 0 signifies error.

Known bugs       : none

See also         : 
@ENDNODE

@NODE "CNetAddressType" "CNetAddressType"
@TOC "MAIN"

Function         : CNetAddressType

Prototype        : UBYTE CNetAddressType( char *user);

Purpose          : Examine the given mail address and discern its type
                   (eg. Internet, local, FTN netmail, etc)

Arguments        : user - the mail address to examine

Returns          : @{"ADDRESSTYPE_*" LINK "cnetinclude:mail.h/main" 292} - see mail.h

Known bugs       : none

See also         : 
@ENDNODE

@NODE "CNetDisposeDir" "CNetDisposeDir"
@TOC "MAIN"

Function         : CNetDisposeDir

Prototype        : void CNetDisposeDir(struct @{"CNetFileEntry" LINK "cnetinclude:files.h/main" 4} **list);

Purpose          : free the COMPLETE file list returned by @{"CNetReadDir()" LINK "CNetReadDir"}

Arguments        : pointer to the list pointer returned by CNetReadDir().
                   Please note that the expected argument is a
                   "pointer to a pointer".

                   upon complete resource deallocation, the pointer "pointed
                   to" by the argument passed to this function is NULLed.

Returns          : none
                   
Known bugs       : none

See also         : 
@ENDNODE

@NODE "CNetIDToUUCP" "CNetIDToUUCP"
@TOC "MAIN"

Function         : CNetIDToUUCP

Prototype        : char *CNetIDToUUCP( LONG userid );

Purpose          : lookup @{"UUCP" LINK "cnetinclude:users.h/main" 154}/MailID from user serial IDNumber

Arguments        : userid - the serial ID for which a mail ID look-up is
                            desired.

Returns          : the mail ID associated with the given ID number.
                   a zero-length return string signifies no match.

Known bugs       : none

See also         : none
@ENDNODE

@NODE "CNetReadDir" "CNetReadDir"
@TOC "MAIN"

Function         : CNetReadDir

Prototype        : struct @{"CNetFileEntry" LINK "cnetinclude:files.h/main" 4} *CNetReadDir(char *path, UBYTE recurse);

Purpose          : Read a complete directory into a linked list of CNetFileEntry
                   structures with parent and child directory retention; with
                   recurse option.

Arguments        : path    - full path to the directory to be read.
                   recurse - TRUE to recurse into sub-directories,
                             FALSE to suppress recursion.

Returns          : pointer to the TOP item in the resultant linked list
                   of CNetFileEntry structures.
                   
Known bugs       : none

See also         : 
@ENDNODE

@NODE "CNetSearchEntry" "CNetSearchEntry"
@TOC "MAIN"

Function         : CNetSearchEntry

Prototype        : struct @{"CNetFileEntry" LINK "cnetinclude:files.h/main" 4} *CNetSearchEntry(struct CNetFileEntry *list, struct CNetFileEntry **destlist, char *pattern, UBYTE recurse);

Purpose          : Search a linked list of CNetFileEntries for a given file pattern.

Arguments        : list     - the list of CNetFileEntry structures to search
                   destlist - a pointer to a list pointer that will be used
                              to store the address of the TOP item in a new
                              linked list of search matches.
                   pattern  - pointer to a filename or pattern to search for.
                   recurse  - TRUE  = recurse into subdirectories
                              FALSE = suppress recursion

Notes            : if the pointer address contained in destlist is NULL,
                   the address of the newly created linked list is stored
                   there and a new list is created.  If destlist is non-NULL,
                   the search entries are appended to the existing list.

                   If recursion is enabled, a full tree of linked lists will
                   be created.  Pay particular attention to this in cases
                   where large directories may be searched.  Recursion can
                   be a large memory resource hog.

Returns          : pointer to the list of search matches
                   
Known bugs       : none

See also         : 
@ENDNODE

